ls and try to work through that.<br><br>That said... I just noticed that there've been many many numbers posted so far.  They've ranged from all sorts of mobs, from the Vindicator, to Yelinak, to the Mist Panther, and all of them have had some sort of flaw with the test (usually in the information given presenting the test, whether with the test or not) that have made them invalid.<br><br>The different tests all yeilded different results.  Because of this, I think it's important to test on many different NPCs, but, 'most particularly' the high end NPCs, like Vindi and Yelinak, as these are the most important ones to us in terms of what we have to tank.  Unfortunately, however, these mobs are among the hardest to get an accurate test on, as they are rarely engaged outside of a raid environment, and inside of a raid environment there are many many many factors to consider which could skew the tests.<br><br>I really don't have any answers, I'm just trying to give a few thoughts to as to the validity of such tests, or, how to make such a test more valid... which I think was your original question? <p><IMG SRC="http://users.starpower.net/dmoser/images/Kaldayr.jpg" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=200></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uadexxeda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adex Xeda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Swift</BR>Steel Warrior Contributor</span><br>  Posts: 346<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/02 2:08:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1011.topic&index=7>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I'm going to test the 1200ac cap Help me develop a plan.</span><hr size=1> Anyone can tell you how it won't work. <br><br>What I'm looking for is that rare individual who has creative solutions as to making it work.<br><br>Unanswered Questions:<br><br>If you are attacked from behind, do you suffer any pentalities in AC?<br><br><br>Is a mob charmed by an enchanter subject to a damage penalty like mage and necro pets when in PvP?<br><br><br> <p><center>Adex Xeda<BR> Warlord<BR> Fires of Heaven</center></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uadexxeda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adex Xeda</A> at: 1/10/02 2:15:11 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/udenardtsf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DenardTSF</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/02 2:38:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1011.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I'm going to test the 1200ac cap Help me develop a plan.</span><hr size=1> Use Yelinak.<br><br>He is perma rooted so you can back out if you need to,  just bring 4-5 clerics and stay alive as long as you can.  You'll get the best results in a controlled single mob encounter against one of this highest ATK mobs in the game.  It would be hard for you to do enough damage to get summoned but I would remove weapons to be safe. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ugrobsmash.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grobsmash</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/02 2:38:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1011.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I'm going to test the 1200ac cap Help me develop a plan.</span><hr size=1> I think the weapon procing would throw off your plan.  Say you start the log at the beginning of the fight a min in to the fight you proc then the fight goes on for 2 min.  then next fight you proc fist swing and you have 3 min fight buffed.  I think your plan would work out nice besides for the proc being uncontrolled also you might want to do it againts some one or something that hits harder and slower then a monk.  Higher damage being done will make it easier to see changes in dmg being taken.  ex. say when you up your ac your dmg taken goes down 10% against a mob hitting for 200 that would drop down to 180 or against a mob hitting for 20 that would go down to 18.  So it would be easier to see small dmg changes.  Also you might want to have someone healing you to make the fight go longer to get a larger data pool. <p>Grobsmash<BR>51 warrior<BR>Provider of sweet troll lovin<BR>Proud member of Eternus Solaris<BR><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=36998>My Gear</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uadexxeda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adex Xeda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Swift</BR>Steel Warrior Contributor</span><br>  Posts: 347<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/02 3:05:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1011.topic&index=10>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I'm going to test the 1200ac cap Help me develop a plan.</span><hr size=1> How about dire charming a lvl 45 frost giant?<br><br><br>I know that there's some easily controlable lvl 60 panther in WL as well.<br><br><br>There might also be a way of determining the effects of AC by closely logging and noting the amount of damage a mob hits you.<br><br>This works under the assumption that over time the same mob will do more damage per hit with lower AC and less damage per hit against higher AC.<br><br>If this could be established all you would have to do is go MT that uber mob and note your current AC and agility. <br><br>After a bunch of fights you could collect the average hit amounts vs. your AC at the time.<br><br>This method would let you get data from a regular raid, however it wouldn't easily allow you to change your AC to a wide range of things. I.E. MT drops down to 900ac on yelnak just to test.<br><br>What is the range that we're most interested in anyway?<br><br>1000ac to 1500ac ?<br><br> <p><center>Adex Xeda<BR> Warlord<BR> Fires of Heaven</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaerildroigheann.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aeril Droigheann</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 294<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/02 3:16:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1011.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: I'm going to test the 1200ac cap Help me develop a plan.</span><hr size=1> Guidelines for testing damage mitigation effects of AC:<br><br>1.  Keep AGI constant, preferably 255.  Put the primal in main hand and offhand a hammer if you have one.  If you really want, have a shaman with PA on backup.<br><br>2.  Pick an NPC that spawns at the same level, if you aren't testing all AC values in the same day.  The mist panther in WL is good for something that is easy to find up.  Other raid mobs like Yelinak are good also.  Things with very high HPs are the best.  If you test against things that you end up killing you will need to make sure to only log when #1 is in effect.<br><br>3.  Get as many data points per AC value as possible.  If you walk up to Yelinak and he kills you in 15 seconds, that isn't a very good test.  Bring a cleric or more depending on who you're testing.<br><br>4.  Test average damage per hit, NOT damage taken per second.  The latter adds a time component into the equation and is just one more variable you need to account for.  It also doesn't help you determine anything above and beyond ADPH in regards to the effects of AC.  ADPH negates the effect of avoidance and lost aggro (in the case of live raid testing like I did).  DPS would be useful for tuning raid encounters but not for what we're testing.<br><br>5.  Disregard special attacks like kick or bash.<br><br>6.  In the case of live raid testing, don't mix up defensive and non-defensive numbers.<br><br>For AC range, I suppose you could go as low as 1000 if you wanted.  1100 is probably a little more practical.  The accepted cap number is in the 1250 area.  As for the high end, go as high as you are possibly able.<br><br>One thing that would be interesting also is to test X AC unbuffed + AC buffs to bring you to Y AC and then compare that vs. Y AC unbuffed. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=45589">Aeryl Firebrand</a>, Warlord<br><a href="http://interealms.com/profiles/profile.cfm?ID=4080">Aeril Droigheann</a>, 59 Preserver, Semi-Retired<br><a href="http://berglad.stormloader.com/">Undaunted</a>, Xegony<br></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaerildroigheann.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aeril Droigheann</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BOR